# BEC Web Design Guide
Visual and interaction rules to keep the site consistent. Reference this for color, type, layout, components, imagery, and motion.

## Mobile First
- Always design and code the website mobile first.

## Brand Palette (OKLCH tokens in `globals.css`)
- Primary: Burnt orange `--primary` (accent and CTAs), foreground on white.
- Secondary: Dark blue-gray `--secondary` for nav, text accents.
- Accent: Secondary orange `--accent` for highlights and hovers.
- Surface: `--background`/`--card` is white; dark mode uses `--background` dark.
- Borders: `--border` soft neutral for separators.
- Destructive: `--destructive` for warnings only.
- Charts: `--chart-1`…`--chart-5` reserved for data viz.

## Typography
- Sans: Geist (`--font-sans`) for all text; Mono reserved for code snippets only.
- Headings: Uppercase, tight leading for hero statements; otherwise sentence case.
- Body: Use `text-foreground`; keep comfortable line height (`leading-relaxed` on paragraphs).
- Emphasis: Prefer weight changes over color. Avoid underlines except for links.

## Layout and Spacing
- Grid: Constrain content with `container mx-auto px-4`; allow widescreen hero visuals edge-to-edge when needed.
- Rhythm: Use consistent vertical spacing steps (e.g., 8/12/16/24/32px translated to Tailwind spacing). Avoid mixing arbitrary values unless for hero art direction.
- Cards/blocks: Zero-radius by default (`--radius: 0`). Apply subtle shadow sparingly; rely on contrast and spacing.
- Sections: Each home section should be visually distinct via spacing, background tint, or imagery—no heavy borders.

## Components (shadcn/ui + Tailwind)
- Buttons: Use primary for CTAs, secondary/ghost for navigation or tertiary actions. Keep ample padding and clear hover states.
- Navigation: Desktop uses shadcn navigation-menu with hover panels; mobile uses sheet/drawer. Maintain keyboard focus styles.
- Links: Underline on hover; use accent color for emphasis only when link density is low.
- Chips/badges: Use muted backgrounds with foreground text for categorization, not primary.

### Shared building blocks (`src/components/common/`) — reuse these, don't re-roll
Canonical patterns; any new page must use them so every listing looks identical.
- **`SectionHeading`** — every section title (optional uppercase eyebrow + `h2` + supporting paragraph). Don't hand-write `<h2>` heading blocks.
- **`PersonCard` / `PersonGrid`** — the card for governance people (leadership, deans, officers, HODs, Board of Governors, Sangha). Department faculty use `FacultyCard` (below), not this. Uniform `aspect-4/3` photo (initials fallback when no photo), name, optional description line, `badges` (`primary` tone for the role; `muted`/`outline` for status like "To confirm"/"Awaiting update"), optional email. Photos are R2 URLs via `asset()`.
- **`FacultyCard`** (`components/programs/faculty/`) — the department-faculty card. Horizontal row: a circular portrait (`h-16 w-16`, `ring-2 ring-stone-100` → `group-hover:ring-primary/20`, initials fallback) on the **left**, name + designation on the **right**, and a far-right `ChevronRight` that nudges + turns `primary` on hover. The whole row is clickable — it opens the member's profile/CV PDF in a modal viewer (`<iframe>` + an "Open" button). Driven by `FacultyMember` (`{ name, designation, photoUrl?, cvUrl? }`); members with no `cvUrl` render as a static (non-clickable) row with no chevron. Grid is `grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-3` (rows need more width than `PersonCard` tiles).
- **`FilterChips`** — single-select category/segment filtering that wraps cleanly (e.g. Board of Governors by category, gallery filters). Use this, **not** the `Tabs` primitive, for many wrapping filters; reserve `Tabs` for a small fixed segmented control.
- **`LeadershipMessage`** — full layout for any "message from a leader" page (Principal, Chairman, Director…): standard eyebrow/title header, sticky portrait + name card with optional pull-quote, body paragraphs, optional achievements panel, and a signature block. Pass the message as a string (blank lines = paragraphs). Don't re-create bespoke message-page layouts.
- Cards use `rounded-sm` + `border-stone-200` + subtle `shadow-sm`; people grids are `sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3`. Match this for any new directory/listing.

## Imagery and Media
- Hero: Parallax video for desktop, still image fallback for mobile. Always apply a dark or warm overlay for text readability.
- Photography: Prefer campus life and people-centric shots. Maintain consistent color warmth; avoid clashing filters.
- Logos: Use `/logo.png` or `/logo.jpg` on light backgrounds; add subtle drop or contrast outline on busy imagery if required.

## Motion and Interaction
- Parallax: Keep current 50% scroll speed; ensure text remains readable.
- Entrance/hover: Use small translate/opacity changes; keep durations short (150–250ms) and ease-out.
- Avoid motion that hides essential content; ensure focus states are always visible even when animated.

## Accessibility and Contrast
- Maintain contrast using palette tokens; avoid custom colors outside token set.
- Provide meaningful `alt` text on images and videos. Do not use text baked into images for essential content.
- Respect focus outlines from shadcn/ui; never remove them.

## Responsive Behavior
- Mobile-first: Ensure layouts stack cleanly; generous tap targets for nav and CTAs.
- Desktop: Use breathing room; avoid cramming columns. Keep hero typography large and bold.
- Breakpoints: Continue using `md`/`lg` patterns already present in hero and nav; verify readability at each step.

## Content Tone
- Confident, institutional, and clear. Short headlines; supportive subcopy. Avoid marketing fluff.

## Usage Notes
- When creating new sections, start with existing home section patterns for spacing, headings, and background treatments.
- Reuse tokens and components before introducing new styles. If a new pattern is needed, add the style to this guide. 
